VALUES
(44, 3, 1, 19, 55, 17, 17, 'hour of prayer', 'Connection of Prayer Times', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on prayer at specific times. Both passages mention the act of praying, with Acts noting the hour of prayer and Psalms referencing multiple times of prayer.', 'theme', 0.44699999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 44, 10, 3, 3, 'the ninth hour', 'Connection of Prayer Timing', 'Both passages emphasize the ''ninth hour'' as a significant time for prayer and divine encounters. This connection highlights the importance of this hour in the early Christian community.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 44, 4, 13, 13, NULL, 'Boldness of Peter and John', 'This connection highlights the transformation of Peter and John from ordinary men to bold witnesses. Both passages emphasize their actions in the temple and their relationship with Jesus.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 42, 1, 10, 10, 'hour of prayer', 'Prayer Timing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize specific times of prayer. Acts mentions the ''hour of prayer,'' while Luke refers to the ''time of incense,'' indicating a shared practice of communal prayer in the temple.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 42, 24, 53, 53, 'temple', 'Temple Worship Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worship in the temple. Both passages emphasize the importance of being in the temple, with Peter and John going there for prayer and the disciples continually praising God.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 27, 6, 10, 10, 'the hour of prayer', 'Prayer Practices in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the act of prayer at specific times. Peter and John go to the temple for prayer, while Daniel prays three times a day. This connection highlights the importance of regular prayer in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 1, 27, 9, 21, 21, 'the hour of prayer', 'Prayer Timing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize specific times of prayer, with Acts noting the ''hour of prayer'' and Daniel referencing ''the time of the evening oblation.'' This connection highlights the significance of prayer in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 44, 14, 8, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Crippled Individuals', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who are ''crippled from their mother’s womb,'' highlighting their lifelong disabilities. This connection underscores the theme of healing and restoration found in the ministry of the apostles.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 43, 9, 8, 8, 'to ask alms of them', 'Connection of Lameness and Begging', 'This connection highlights the theme of disability and begging in both passages. The man in Acts is lame and asks for alms, while the man in John is blind and also begs, illustrating a shared experience of physical limitation and dependence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 42, 16, 20, 20, NULL, 'Connection of Beggars and Lameness', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who are in need and are laid at gates, highlighting their vulnerability and dependence on others for support. The mention of being ''laid'' suggests a similar situation of helplessness in both accounts.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 42, 18, 35, 35, NULL, 'Begging for Alms', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who are disabled and begging for assistance. The lame man in Acts and the blind man in Luke share a similar plight, highlighting the theme of dependence on others for support.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 44, 10, 31, 31, 'alms', 'Connection of Almsgiving', 'Both passages emphasize the act of giving alms, highlighting its significance in the lives of the faithful. The lame man at the temple gate seeks alms, while Cornelius''s alms are remembered by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 2, 43, 1, 9, 30, NULL, 'Healing and Light Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the transformative power of Jesus. The lame man''s healing in Acts symbolizes the spiritual light and grace that Jesus brings to the world, as described in John. This connection highlights the physical and spiritual restoration offered through Christ.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 4, 44, 14, 9, 10, 'fastening his eyes upon him', 'Healing through Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the act of beholding someone with intention before a healing occurs. Peter and Paul both focus their attention on the individuals, leading to miraculous healings based on the perceived faith of the recipients.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 4, 43, 11, 40, 40, 'Look on us', 'Seeing and Believing', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeing linked to belief. In Acts, Peter encourages the man to look, while in John, Jesus emphasizes that belief leads to seeing God''s glory.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 4, 42, 4, 20, 20, 'fastening his eyes upon him', 'Focus of Attention', 'This connection highlights the act of people focusing their attention on significant figures. In both passages, the phrase ''eyes...fastened'' indicates a moment of intense observation and expectation towards Peter and Jesus.', 'keyword', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 4, 44, 3, 12, 12, 'Look on us', 'Focus on Peter and John', 'This connection highlights the emphasis on the gaze directed towards Peter and John in both passages. In Acts 3:4, Peter instructs the man to ''Look on us,'' and in Acts 3:12, he questions why the people are looking ''so earnestly on us.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 4, 43, 5, 6, 6, 'Look on us', 'Healing and Attention', 'Both passages emphasize the act of looking and the desire for healing. Peter''s command to ''Look on us'' parallels Jesus'' inquiry about the man''s willingness to be made whole, highlighting the importance of attention in the healing process.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 44, 3, 16, 16, 'in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Connection of Healing in Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the power of faith in Jesus'' name to bring healing. Peter''s declaration in the first passage sets the stage for the miracle described in the second, where faith in that name results in strength and soundness.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 44, 4, 10, 10, 'in the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth', 'Connection of Healing in Jesus'' Name', 'Both passages emphasize the power of healing through the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth. In Acts 3:6, Peter invokes Jesus'' name to heal a man, while Acts 4:10 reiterates that this healing is accomplished by the same name, highlighting its significance.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 41, 16, 17, 17, 'In the name of Jesus Christ', 'Connection of Healing in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the authority of Jesus'' name in performing miracles. Both passages emphasize the power believers have to act in Jesus'' name, leading to healing and signs.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 47, 8, 9, 9, 'silver and gold have I none', 'Connection of Riches and Poverty', 'This connection highlights the contrast between material wealth and spiritual richness. In Acts, Peter offers healing in Jesus'' name, emphasizing spiritual wealth over silver and gold, while 2 Corinthians speaks of Jesus becoming poor for our sake, allowing us to gain spiritual richness.', 'theme', 0.391, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 59, 2, 5, 5, 'none', 'Connection of Faith and Poverty', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s favor towards the poor and their rich faith. In Acts, Peter''s healing act demonstrates that spiritual wealth transcends material poverty, aligning with James'' assertion that God has chosen the poor as heirs of the kingdom.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 60, 4, 10, 10, 'such as I have give I thee', 'Stewardship of Gifts', 'This connection highlights the theme of using one''s gifts for the benefit of others. In Acts 3:6, Peter offers healing in the name of Jesus, while 1 Peter 4:10 encourages believers to minister their gifts to one another.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 6, 40, 7, 22, 22, 'in the name of Jesus Christ', 'Authority in Jesus'' Name', 'This connection highlights the power of invoking Jesus'' name. In Acts, Peter heals in Jesus'' name, while in Matthew, individuals claim to perform works in His name, emphasizing the significance of authority derived from Jesus.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 7, 41, 1, 31, 31, 'took him by the right hand, and lifted him up', 'Healing Through Lifting Up', 'Both passages emphasize the act of taking someone by the hand and lifting them up, resulting in immediate healing. This connection highlights the theme of restoration and empowerment through physical touch.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 7, 41, 9, 27, 27, 'and lifted him up', 'Healing Through Lifting Up', 'Both passages emphasize the act of Jesus lifting someone up, resulting in restoration and strength. This connection highlights a theme of divine intervention and healing.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 7, 41, 5, 41, 41, 'took him by the right hand', 'Healing and Resurrection Motif', 'Both passages emphasize the act of lifting or taking by the hand to restore life and strength. This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing and resurrection in the ministry of Jesus and the apostles.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 7, 44, 9, 41, 41, 'lifted him up', 'Miraculous Healings and Resurrections', 'Both passages emphasize the act of lifting someone up, resulting in restoration and new life. In Acts 3:7, the man receives strength, while in Acts 9:41, the woman is presented alive.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 7, 42, 13, 13, 13, 'immediately', 'Healing through Touch', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying hands to bring about healing. In Acts, the man receives strength, while in Luke, the woman is made straight, showcasing a theme of restoration through physical touch.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 23, 35, 6, 6, 'leaping up stood, and walked', 'Healing and Restoration Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing and restoration, particularly the transformation of the lame. In Acts, the man is described as ''walking, and leaping, and praising God,'' which parallels Isaiah''s prophecy of the lame man leaping.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 44, 14, 10, 10, 'leaping up stood, and walked', 'Healing and Praise Connection', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healing resulting in leaping and walking. The physical response of leaping and walking in both instances highlights the transformative power of faith and divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 19, 107, 20, 22, 'praising God', 'Praise for Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing and the response of praise. Acts 3:8 describes a man who, after being healed, praises God, while Psalms 107:20-22 calls for men to praise the Lord for His goodness and healing works.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 19, 103, 1, 2, 'praising God', 'Praise and Blessing Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of praising God found in both passages. In Acts 3:8, the healed man is ''praising God,'' while Psalms 103:1-2 calls for the soul to ''bless the Lord.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 42, 6, 23, 23, 'leaping, and praising God', 'Joyful Leaping Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of leaping as an expression of joy. In Acts, the healed man leaps and praises God, while in Luke, believers are encouraged to leap for joy in anticipation of their reward.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 42, 17, 15, 18, 'praising God', 'Praise and Gratitude for Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the act of praising God after healing. In Acts, the healed man ''leaping up'' and ''praising God'' parallels the Samaritan who ''glorified God'' and gave thanks in Luke.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 8, 43, 5, 14, 14, 'praising God', 'Healing and Worship Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of praising God following healing. In Acts, the healed man praises God in the temple, while in John, Jesus finds a healed man in the temple, reinforcing the theme of worship after restoration.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 9, 42, 13, 17, 17, NULL, 'Public Reaction to Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the public''s response to miraculous events. In Acts, the people see a man walking and praising God, while in Luke, they rejoice over the glorious things done by Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 9, 44, 4, 16, 16, 'walking and praising God', 'Miracle Recognition in Jerusalem', 'Both passages emphasize the public acknowledgment of a miracle. In Acts 3:9, the healed man is seen ''walking and praising God,'' which leads to the recognition of this miracle in Acts 4:16 as undeniable by the people in Jerusalem.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 9, 44, 4, 21, 21, 'praising God', 'Praise and Glorification of God', 'Both passages emphasize the public response of people glorifying God after witnessing miraculous events. In Acts 3:9, the healed man is seen walking and praising God, which leads to a collective glorification in Acts 4:21.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 9, 41, 2, 11, 12, 'praising God', 'Healing and Praise Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of healing leading to public praise of God. In Acts, the healed man walks and praises God, while in Mark, the healed man also glorifies God after his miracle.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 9, 44, 14, 11, 11, 'walking and praising God', 'Public Response to Miracles', 'Both passages emphasize the public''s reaction to miraculous events. In Acts 3, the healed man is seen ''walking and praising God,'' while in Acts 14, the people respond to Paul''s miracle by declaring him a god. This connection highlights the theme of divine acts prompting human praise and recognition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 44, 3, 2, 2, 'at the Beautiful gate of the temple', 'Connection of Healing and Recognition', 'Both passages emphasize the man at the Beautiful gate, highlighting his condition and the subsequent amazement of the people. The first passage describes his daily presence asking for alms, while the second reflects the wonder at his healing.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 42, 9, 43, 43, 'filled with wonder and amazement', 'Amazement at God''s Power', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of people filled with wonder and amazement at miraculous events. In Acts, the crowd is amazed at the healing of a man, while in Luke, they are amazed at the mighty power of God demonstrated through Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 43, 5, 20, 20, 'filled with wonder and amazement', 'Connection of Wonder and Marvel', 'This connection highlights the theme of wonder and amazement in both passages. In Acts 3:10, the people are filled with wonder at the healing, while in John 5:20, the Father will show greater works that cause marvel.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 43, 9, 3, 3, 'filled with wonder and amazement', 'Connection of Healing and Wonder', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous healing leading to wonder. In both passages, the results of divine intervention evoke amazement, as seen in the healed man at the temple and the man born blind.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 42, 4, 36, 36, 'filled with wonder and amazement', 'Connection of Amazement and Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of amazement in response to miraculous events. In Acts, the crowd is filled with wonder at the healing, while in Luke, they are amazed by Jesus'' authoritative command over unclean spirits.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 10, 44, 2, 7, 7, 'filled with wonder and amazement', 'Amazement and Wonder', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of amazement experienced by the people witnessing miraculous events. In Acts 3:10, the crowd is filled with wonder and amazement at the healing, while in Acts 2:7, they marvel at the Galileans speaking in tongues.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 11, 44, 5, 12, 12, NULL, 'Connection through Solomon''s Porch', 'Both passages emphasize the location of Solomon''s porch, where significant events occurred involving the apostles and the people. The healing of the lame man in Acts 3 leads to further signs and wonders in the same location in Acts 5.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 11, 42, 8, 38, 38, NULL, 'Healing and Transformation', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing and transformation in both passages. In Acts, the healed lame man draws attention to the miraculous work of Peter and John, while in Luke, the man freed from demons seeks to follow Jesus, indicating a significant change in his life.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 11, 43, 10, 23, 23, 'the porch that is called Solomon’s', 'Connection through Solomon''s Porch', 'Both passages emphasize Solomon''s porch as a significant location. Acts 3:11 describes a miraculous event occurring there, while John 10:23 notes Jesus walking in the same area.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 11, 42, 22, 8, 8, 'Peter and John', 'Connection Between Peter and John', 'Both passages emphasize the roles of Peter and John in significant events. In Acts, they are central to a miraculous healing, while in Luke, they are tasked with preparing for the Passover.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 11, 44, 2, 6, 6, 'all the people ran together unto them', 'Gathering of the Multitude', 'Both passages emphasize the gathering of people in response to miraculous events. In Acts 3:11, the healing of the lame man draws a crowd, similar to how the events in Acts 2:6 cause the multitude to come together.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 47, 3, 5, 5, 'our own power or holiness', 'Sufficiency and Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of reliance on God rather than personal ability. Both passages emphasize that human sufficiency and power come from God, not from oneself.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 43, 3, 27, 28, 'by our own power or holiness', 'Source of Power and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine authority in both passages. Peter emphasizes that the healing was not by their own power, while John asserts that a man can receive nothing except it be given from heaven.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 1, 41, 16, 16, NULL, 'Divine Power Acknowledgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of acknowledging God''s power in miraculous events. Both Peter and Joseph emphasize that it is not their own abilities, but God''s intervention that brings about significant outcomes.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 27, 2, 28, 30, 'by our own power or holiness', 'Divine Power and Revelation', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power in both passages. Peter emphasizes that the healing was not by their own power, while Daniel acknowledges that the revelation of secrets comes from God, not from his own wisdom.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 44, 14, 11, 15, NULL, 'Humanity of Apostles', 'Both passages emphasize the humanity of the apostles, as they reject the notion of divine power attributed to them. Peter and Paul both clarify that they are merely men, urging the people to recognize the true source of their miracles.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 44, 2, 22, 22, 'by our own power or holiness', 'Connection of Divine Power', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine power at work. Both passages emphasize that the miracles performed are not by human ability but through God''s authority, as seen in Peter''s assertion of their lack of power in healing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 12, 45, 9, 4, 4, 'Ye men of Israel', 'Connection of Israelite Identity', 'This connection highlights the identity of the Israelites as recipients of God''s promises and the role of Peter in affirming their significance. Both passages emphasize the importance of divine power and holiness in the context of Israel''s covenant relationship with God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 40, 22, 32, 32, 'the God of Abraham, and of Isaac, and of Jacob', 'Connection of God''s Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of God as the God of Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s relationship with His people, affirming that He is a living God who glorifies Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 44, 7, 32, 32, 'the God of Abraham, and of Isaac, and of Jacob', 'Connection of the God of Fathers', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of God as ''the God of Abraham, and of Isaac, and of Jacob.'' This connection highlights the continuity of God''s relationship with His people from Moses to the time of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 2, 3, 6, 6, 'the God of Abraham, and of Isaac, and of Jacob', 'Connection of God''s Identity', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of God as ''the God of Abraham, and of Isaac, and of Jacob.'' This connection highlights the continuity of God''s relationship with His people from the time of Moses to the time of the apostles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 40, 27, 17, 25, 'whom ye delivered up, and denied him', 'Denial of Jesus by the Crowd', 'Both passages emphasize the denial of Jesus by the people, with Acts referencing their actions in delivering him up, while Matthew details their choice to release Barabbas instead of Jesus. This connection highlights the collective rejection of Jesus in favor of a criminal.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 42, 23, 16, 23, 'whom ye delivered up, and denied him', 'Connection of Jesus'' Denial', 'Both passages emphasize the denial of Jesus by the crowd. Acts 3:13 mentions the delivery and denial of Jesus, while Luke 23:21-23 describes the crowd''s demand for his crucifixion instead of Barabbas.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 43, 18, 40, 40, 'denied him in the presence of Pilate', 'Denial of Jesus and Barabbas', 'This connection highlights the choice made by the crowd to deny Jesus in favor of Barabbas. Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus, with Acts referencing the denial before Pilate and John depicting the crowd''s demand for Barabbas.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 13, 43, 19, 12, 12, 'when he was determined to let him go', 'Pilate''s Role in Jesus'' Trial', 'Both passages emphasize Pilate''s determination to release Jesus. Acts 3:13 mentions Pilate''s intention, while John 19:12 shows the pressure he faced from the Jews to deny that release.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 41, 1, 24, 24, 'the Holy One', 'Connection of the Holy One', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''the Holy One.'' Acts 3:14 highlights the rejection of this figure, while Mark 1:24 acknowledges His divine nature and authority.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 44, 7, 52, 52, NULL, 'Connection of Betrayal and Murder', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of betrayal and murder associated with the Just One. Acts 3:14 mentions the denial of the Holy One, while Acts 7:52 refers to the betrayal and murder of the Just One, linking the two events.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 44, 4, 27, 27, 'the Holy One', 'Denial of Jesus and Conspiracy', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection of Jesus, highlighting the collective responsibility of various groups in denying ''the Holy One.'' This connection illustrates the theme of opposition against Jesus, culminating in his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 60, 3, 18, 18, 'the Just', 'Connection of Just and Unjust', 'This connection highlights the contrast between ''the Just'' in Acts 3:14 and ''the just for the unjust'' in 1 Peter 3:18. Both passages emphasize the righteousness of Christ in relation to humanity''s sinfulness.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 59, 5, 6, 6, 'the Just', 'Connection of Justice and Condemnation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of condemning the just. Acts 3:14 speaks of denying ''the Just,'' while James 5:6 mentions ''killed the just,'' highlighting a parallel in the treatment of righteous individuals.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 38, 9, 9, 9, 'the Just', 'Connection of Justice and Kingship', 'This connection highlights the theme of justice in both passages. Acts 3:14 refers to Jesus as ''the Just,'' while Zechariah 9:9 describes the coming King as ''just'' and ''having salvation.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 14, 42, 23, 18, 19, 'desired a murderer to be granted unto you', 'Denial of Jesus and Barabbas', 'Both passages emphasize the choice between Jesus and a murderer, Barabbas. Acts 3:14 highlights the denial of the ''Holy One'' in favor of a criminal, paralleling the crowd''s demand in Luke 23:18-19.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 15, 44, 2, 24, 24, 'whom God hath raised from the dead', 'Resurrection of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize God''s act of raising Jesus from the dead. Acts 3:15 refers to Jesus as the ''Prince of life,'' while Acts 2:24 states that God ''hath raised up'' Jesus, highlighting the central theme of resurrection.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 15, 44, 2, 32, 32, 'whereof we are witnesses', 'Resurrection Witnesses Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of resurrection and the role of witnesses. They highlight that Jesus was raised from the dead, with the apostles affirming their witness to this event.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 15, 66, 21, 6, 6, 'Prince of life', 'Connection of Life and Water', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of life. Acts 3:15 refers to Jesus as the ''Prince of life,'' while Revelation 21:6 speaks of the ''fountain of the water of life.'' This connection highlights the theme of life as central to the message of both texts.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 3, 15, 43, 1, 4, 4, 'Prince of life', 'Connection of Life and Light', 'This connection highlights the theme of life present in both passages. Acts 3:15 refers to Jesus as the ''Prince of life,'' while John 1:4 states that ''in him was life,'' emphasizing the significance of life in relation to Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
